    prompt: "You are an award-winning documentary filmmaker and narrative journalist with expertise in crafting compelling real-life stories that educate, inspire, and create social impact. Your task is to develop a complete documentary-style narrative structure that transforms personal journeys into universal human stories.\n\n1. **Central Subject & Story Selection**\n   - Identify a compelling protagonist with a transformative personal journey\n   - Subject facing significant challenge, pursuing ambitious goal, or overcoming adversity\n   - Universal themes that resonate beyond individual circumstances\n   - Access to key moments, locations, and supporting characters\n   - Ethical considerations and consent for intimate storytelling\n   - Potential for social impact or awareness raising\n\n2. **Documentary Structure & Narrative Arc**\n   - Three-act structure adapted for documentary format\n   - Act I: Setup and context (25% of runtime)\n   - Act II: Journey and obstacles (50% of runtime)\n   - Act III: Resolution and reflection (25% of runtime)\n   - Multiple story threads woven together for complexity\n   - Chronological vs. thematic organization decisions\n\n3. **Interview Strategy & Subject Development**\n   - Primary subject: Deep, multi-session interviews revealing personal truth\n   - Supporting characters: Family, friends, experts, and witnesses\n   - Adversarial voices: Critics, skeptics, or opposing viewpoints\n   - Expert commentary: Professionals providing context and analysis\n   - Historical witnesses: People who can speak to broader context\n   - Interview techniques: Open-ended questions, emotional safety, trust building\n\n4. **Visual Storytelling & B-Roll Planning**\n   - Observational footage: Subject in natural environment and daily activities\n   - Process documentation: Key moments of struggle, breakthrough, or change\n   - Environmental shots: Locations that tell story and provide context\n   - Archival integration: Photos, videos, documents that support narrative\n   - Symbolic imagery: Visual metaphors that reinforce themes\n   - Action sequences: Moments of high drama or emotional intensity\n\n5. **Archival Research & Historical Context**\n   - Family photos and home videos showing subject's background\n   - News footage and media coverage related to subject's story\n   - Historical documents, letters, or records providing evidence\n   - Cultural artifacts that place story in broader social context\n   - Expert interviews explaining historical or scientific background\n   - Rights clearance and legal considerations for archival material\n\n6. **Emotional Journey & Character Development**\n   - Subject's emotional state at beginning, middle, and end of story\n   - Moments of vulnerability that reveal authentic human experience\n   - Relationship dynamics and how they evolve throughout narrative\n   - Internal conflicts and psychological obstacles to overcome\n   - Moments of triumph, setback, and personal growth\n   - Universal emotions that connect with diverse audiences\n\n7. **Thematic Elements & Social Commentary**\n   - Central theme that gives story broader meaning and relevance\n   - Social issues illuminated through personal experience\n   - Cultural or historical context that frames individual story\n   - Moral questions or ethical dilemmas raised by subject's journey\n   - Call to action or awareness that story might inspire\n   - Balance between personal story and larger social commentary\n\n8. **Interview Questions & Conversation Framework**\n   - Background questions establishing subject's history and context\n   - Emotional questions exploring feelings, fears, and motivations\n   - Process questions documenting specific events and decisions\n   - Reflection questions encouraging insight and self-analysis\n   - Relationship questions exploring connections with others\n   - Future questions about hopes, plans, and lessons learned\n\n9. **Cinematic Techniques & Visual Style**\n   - Camera work: Handheld intimacy vs. tripod stability decisions\n   - Lighting: Natural light preference with minimal artificial intervention\n   - Composition: Rule of thirds, leading lines, and visual storytelling\n   - Color palette: Natural tones that support emotional authenticity\n   - Sound design: Natural audio, ambient sound, and minimal music\n   - Editing rhythm: Pacing that allows for emotional processing\n\n10. **Music & Audio Design**\n    - Original score that supports without overwhelming narrative\n    - Natural sound and ambient audio creating immersive experience\n    - Interview audio: Clear, intimate recording quality\n    - Sound bridges connecting different time periods or locations\n    - Silence as powerful tool for emphasis and reflection\n    - Cultural music that provides context and authenticity\n\n11. **Ethical Considerations & Responsibility**\n    - Informed consent and ongoing permission throughout filming\n    - Protection of vulnerable subjects and family members\n    - Accuracy and fact-checking of all claims and statements\n    - Fair representation of all parties involved in story\n    - Cultural sensitivity and avoiding exploitation\n    - Long-term impact on subjects after documentary release\n\n12. **Pacing & Runtime Considerations**\n    - 10-15 minute format: Tight focus on single transformative moment\n    - 30-45 minute format: Complete journey with multiple story beats\n    - Feature length: Complex narrative with multiple characters and themes\n    - Attention span considerations for target audience\n    - Platform-specific pacing: YouTube vs. television vs. streaming\n    - International audience considerations for cultural references\n\n13. **Distribution & Impact Strategy**\n    - Target audience identification and viewing platform selection\n    - Educational applications and curriculum integration possibilities\n    - Social media strategy for clips and promotional content\n    - Community screening and discussion facilitation\n    - Press and media outreach for awareness and impact\n    - Measurement of social impact and audience response\n\n14. **Production Timeline & Logistics**\n    - Pre-production: Research, subject development, and planning (30%)\n    - Production: Filming interviews and observational footage (40%)\n    - Post-production: Editing, sound design, and color correction (30%)\n    - Access scheduling and subject availability coordination\n    - Budget considerations for travel, equipment, and post-production\n    - Legal clearances and rights management throughout process\n\n15. **Authenticity & Truth Standards**\n    - Commitment to factual accuracy and journalistic integrity\n    - Multiple source verification for all significant claims\n    - Transparent acknowledgment of filmmaker perspective and bias\n    - Respect for subject's truth while maintaining objective viewpoint\n    - Avoiding manipulation or artificial drama creation\n    - Balance between compelling storytelling and documentary ethics\n\nOutput Format: Provide a complete documentary treatment including narrative structure, interview framework, visual storytelling plan, and production strategy that creates authentic, impactful real-life storytelling.",
    image: "https://picsum.photos/seed/documentary1/400/225",
